{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622445"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16800"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16800"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.16,0.36,0,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9491"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5161"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22894"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGabapentinoids are medications commonly prescribed for neuropathic pain and epilepsy. They have a unique mechanism of action that differs from other anticonvulsants.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of gabapentinoids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks potassium channels","Inhibits glutamate receptors","Binds to alpha-2-delta subunit of calcium channels","Blocks sodium channels","Enhances gamma-aminobutyric acid synthesis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGabapentinoids (pregabalin and gabapentin) primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to the alpha-2-delta subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E. This reduces calcium influx into neurons, which decreases the release of excitatory neurotransmitters like glutamate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks potassium channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Gabapentinoids do not significantly interact with potassium channels in the central nervous system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits glutamate receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - While gabapentinoids reduce glutamate release, they do not directly interact with or block glutamate receptors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism belongs to other anticonvulsants such as carbamazepine and phenytoin, but is not how gabapentinoids work.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances gamma-aminobutyric acid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Despite their name suggesting a structural similarity to GABA, gabapentinoids do not significantly affect GABA synthesis or function.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe reduction in excitatory neurotransmitter release through calcium channel modulation explains their therapeutic effects in both neuropathic pain and epilepsy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gabapentinoids bind to the alpha-2-delta subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels in the central nervous system.","By reducing calcium influx, gabapentinoids decrease the release of excitatory neurotransmitters like glutamate.","Gabapentinoids are primarily used to treat neuropathic pain and epilepsy."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16800"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T16:35:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T16:37:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9491"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68374"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCou